%md
# Exploratory data analysis and data wrangling of dataset from the Lab
#### In this script, we aim to use scala/spark and spark sql to perform exploratory analysis and data wrangling on lab test data. We plan to do initial data exploratory analysis to identify potential data issue such as missing values or uncleared labels. Then, we are going to clean those data if there are any. Finally, we will perform descriptive statistic analysis to analyze potential features. To do that, we need to import libraries first.

result.msg:

We plan to do initial data exploratory analysis to identify potential data issue such as missing values or uncleared labels. Then, we are going to clean those data if there are any. Finally, we will perform descriptive statistic analysis to analyze potential features. To do that, we need to import libraries first.

### 1.1 Merge lab results with enrolled patients to get data for study 
#### In order to get the data that we are going to use for this study, we merge the lab results with selected patients for invastigation. We need lab type, test name, test value and run date for our analysis and future feature construction. First, we define two case classes and define the class values as string.

paragraphs.text:
val labRDD_key = labRDD_cleaned
    .map(line => line.split(","))
    .filter(line => !line(0).contains("PATNO"))
    .map(line => LabResult(line(0).toString.toUpperCase, line(1).toString.toUpperCase, line(2).toString.toUpperCase, line(4).toString.toUpperCase,  line(5).toString.toUpperCase, line(6).toString.toUpperCase, line(3).toString.toUpperCase))
    .map(line=>(line.patientNo, line))
    
val patientsRDD_key = patientsRDD
    .map(line => line.split(","))
    .filter(line => !line(0).contains("record_id"))
    .map(line => Patient(line(1).toString.toUpperCase, line(2).toString.toUpperCase, line(3).toInt, line(4).toString.toUpperCase))
    .map(line=>(line.patientNo, line))

val labMergedRDD = patientsRDD_key.leftOuterJoin(labRDD_key)
labMergedRDD.take(5).foreach(println)

%md 
## 5. Conclusions
#### In this script, we used scala/spark and spark sql to perform exploratory analysis and data wrangling on lab test data. We found that there are 9 enrolled PRODROMAL samples do not have any lab test data. We also noticed that there are duplicated labels of gene names (e.g. GAPDH (Rep 1) and GAPDH (Rep 2)), unconvertable non-numberic test values (e.g. below, above) and data points collected not according to standard process of visit (e.g. ST). Those data are either cleaned or removed in order to do the following analysis. Then, we analyze the lab data as grouped by diagnosis and gender. And also analyzed each test type and visulized the changes of mean of test values by time series graphs. We found that actually only CSF HEMOGLOBIN and  CSF ALPHA-SYNUCLEIN tests present in all 3 categories of diagnoses. This analysis thus gives us insight into data wrangling and feature construction for our modeling.

result.msg:
5. Conclusions

In this script, we used scala/spark and spark sql to perform exploratory analysis and data wrangling on lab test data. We found that there are 9 enrolled PRODROMAL samples do not have any lab test data. We also noticed that there are duplicated labels of gene names (e.g. GAPDH (Rep 1) and GAPDH (Rep 2)), unconvertable non-numberic test values (e.g. below, above) and data points collected not according to standard process of visit (e.g. ST). Those data are either cleaned or removed in order to do the following analysis. Then, we analyze the lab data as grouped by diagnosis and gender. And also analyzed each test type and visulized the changes of mean of test values by time series graphs. We found that actually only CSF HEMOGLOBIN and CSF ALPHA-SYNUCLEIN tests present in all 3 categories of diagnoses. This analysis thus gives us insight into data wrangling and feature construction for our modeling.
